<!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:yellow;">&quot;May the bridges I burn light my way&quot;</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=gebbly>Gebbly</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Evoker</span><br>  Posts: 286<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/24/03 10:37 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> surprising</span><hr size=1> I'm surprised at the element of this debate that keeps raising the question of sustained or burst damage.<br>
<br>
It has been stated by many people (wizards and mages) that this pet is intended to be a mini version of the wizard class much like there are mini versions of warriors and rogues.<br>
<br>
Wizards have always done burst damage so surely it is only sensible that mini versions of wizards also do burst damage.<br>
<br>
Clearly making a pet deal burst damage is more complicated to implement in a balanced form than a sustained damage pet for reasons discussed previously but it would be necessary of a &quot;wizard pet&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;But the domain of mages is sustained damage.&quot;<br>
I beleive that the combination of this and the fact that a wizard pet should act like a wizard (i.e. burst damage) is a cause for several of the problems here.<br>
<br>
Surely it comes down to having a wizard pet (including a wizards downsides as well as ups such as burst damage and being oom at times), or having a pet modelled on another class. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=balanzsonofanz>Balanz son of Anz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Channeler</span><br>  Posts: 222<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/24/03 11:13 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Burst versus Sustained</span><hr size=1> I am not sure about the utility of a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;burst damage&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->-type pet.<br>
<br>
As it is, as a mage I <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">can</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> do burst damage well enough.  Indeed, I keep my mana bar pretty full just so I can burn down as needed.  I accept that I cannot do that as well as a wizard, but I still do well enough.<br>
<br>
So how would a burst-DPS pet work?<br>
<br>
The main value of burst DPS is timing.  When it absolutely, positively has to be killed overnight.  Clear an elemental of very little brain is not going to use burst damage well.  It will have no idea when the right time to burn down is.<br>
<br>
What you would have is hard nuking pet that sometimes <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;got lucky,&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and nuked the right mob at the right time.<br>
<br>
Against a single target in a long fight, who cares about the burst damage?  It's all just DPS at that point.  I would rather just have sustained damage, since that is what pets are largely about, at least on the damage side of the equation.<br>
<br>
On the other hand, suppose we did have a hard nuking burst pet that sometimes cast a big nuke.  It would create an opportunity for the mage to follow up with a nuke.<br>
<br>
It just seems to me that either the burst damage would wind up being crappy sustained damage, or if the burst were good enough to be worthwhile, that burst pet plus burst mage would be too good.<br>
<br>
I have not done a model of burst versus sustained, so I am not confident about my conclusions yet, but those are my immediate gut feelings for now.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Razamatazz Pizzazz</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zarbonius>Zarbonius</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Channeler</span><br>  Posts: 209<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/24/03 11:18 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: surprising</span><hr size=1> I think that's a very important point, Gebbly.  Putting aside all concerns about Ice Comet, Lures, etc., wizards are all about burst damage.<br>
<br>
Since normal wizards are damage-limited by mana, and mages' wizard-pets can be cast/reclaimed/recast to essentially give them an unlimited mana pool, any sustained DPS target would necessarily have to be almost the same as the pet's max burst DPS.  <br>
<br>
There were a number of posts on the Magician's tower on how to a) get the fire pet to nuke as much as possible, and b) cast/reclaim the pet when it runs oom, so SOE will have to assume that Mages will use these (valid) techniques to max their pets' usefulness as they tune these changes.  They might have to tweak it a bit so that the fire pet's burst DPS is slightly higher than the other pets' sustained DPS, to compensate for the extra overhead of casting/reclaiming + time lost nuking, but then, that's why it's only on Test atm.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
I dunno - I'm always happy to see other classes get upgrades (especially our Mage brothers), but I can see that balancing this sort of thing will be a tad difficult.  (yes, deliberate understatement)<br>
<br>
Oh, and just FYI for Mages that aren't too familiar with the wizard spell lineup - if the fire pet loses Ice Comet, and casts more Draughts instead, that's a definite UPGRADE.  Draughts are faster casting, more mana efficient (which means reduced overhead from reclaiming/recasting), and since NPCs/pets tend to ignore recast times, a chain-Draughting Fire pet would be a nuking machine.<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=qaman>Qaman</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist</span><br>  Posts: 3273<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/24/03 2:21 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: surprising</span><hr size=1> Actually, I think the biggest problems are the Mages who aren't happy with the limitations their class is designed around who would be more than happy to have a pet get rid of them all in some manner. This is why we see the call for large ice nukes, snare, stuns, lures, and high burst dps as well as sustained dps as good as their other pets. And then they want all this in the same pet.<br>
<br>
To me, this would be pretty much the same as a Wizard asking for Xuzl to be given the same sustained dps as a Mage pet. Most of us would laugh at such a request, but it seems that most of the mages posting here aren't interested in a discussion about balance, but rather ways in which they can get rid of what few limitations they have now. And this already on top of what they get as a casting class. Anyways, you would go a lot farther being reasonable than claiming people are whining when you are asking for things that pretty much seem overpowered in a lot of ways.<br>
<br>
A lot of us have no problems with seeing the Fire pet made better. But we do have problems with seeing the Fire pet made better than all the other pets combined. It shouldn't be better than any other pet, it should be a equal with the other pets. But most of the suggestions I have seen both here and on the mage boards don't want the pet to be an equal. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=4380">Qaman</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
